That would be something like this, I presume:

    declare
       l_yes  varchar2 (1);
    begin
       select max (&#39;Y&#39;)
         into l_yes
         from dual
        where exists
                 (select &#39;Y&#39;
                    from pa_expenditure_items_all paei, pa_expenditures_all pae
                   where     paei.expenditure_id = pae.expenditure_id
                         and pae.incurred_by_person_id = :person_id
                         and cost_distributed_flag = &#39;N&#39;);
    
       if l_yes is null
       then
          message (&#39;Condition is not met&#39;);
          raise form_trigger_failure;
       else
          -- Do something; probably terminate that user
          null;
       end if;
    end;

In the &quot;conditions&quot; field, you don&#39;t put a whole query.  You just put a Boolean expression (such as you would put in the `WHERE` clause of a query).

So, instead of what you&#39;ve got, try this:

    exists (select &#39;Y&#39;
            from pa_expenditure_items_all paei,
                 pa_expenditures_all pae
            where paei.expenditure_id = pae.expenditure_id and
                  pae.incurred_by_person_id  = :person_id and
                  cost_distributed_flag = &#39;N&#39;
           )

The `:person_id` assumes that `PERSON_ID` is a field in the block that your Forms trigger is firing on.  Better to use the `:block.field` form to make it a little more explicit.

